{"word":"ἀλιταίνω","slug":"ἀλιταίνω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>ἀλιταίνω</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b>root <el>ΑΛΙΤ</el>\n<br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><el>ἀλιτήμενος</el> is formed as if from <el>ἀλίτημι</el>\n<p/><div class='li750'><b>1. </b><a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> <a href='S:person, personal'>pers.</a> <i>to sin</i> or <i>offend against</i> a god, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> rei, <i>to transgress</i>, <el>Διὸς ἐφετμάς</el> <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>3. </b>the <a href='S:participle'>part.</a> <el>ἀλιτήμενος</el> is used as an <a href='S:Adjective'>adj.</a>, <i>sinful</i>, <b><a href='S:Odyssey'>Od.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}